culmination of a series of changes first set in motion in the early 1990s.The Evolution of Japan's Party System analyses the transition by examining both party politics and public policy. Arguing that these political changes were evolutionary rather than revolutionary, the essays in this volume discuss how older parties such as the LDP and the Japan Socialist Party failed to adapt to the new policy environment of the 1990s. Taken as a whole, The Evolution of Japan's Party System provides a unique look at party politics in Japan, bringing them into a comparative conversation that usually focuses on Europe and North America.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 4aDISCOUNT-B. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh1 aIriye, Akira, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacLachlan, Patricia L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartin, Sherry L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiura, Mari, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReed, Steven R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchoppa, Leonard J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTanaka, Aiji, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aToyoda, A. Maria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWeiner, Robert J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977240uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144269542940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442695429423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442695429.jpg  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook 